summary.seg: This Greek manuscript contains a commentary on the Psalms by Euthymius Zigabenus, a Byzantine theologian of the early 12th century, and a commentary on the biblical canticles attributed to the same author, but with less certainty. The texts are both incomplete. In the commentary on the Psalms there are three lacunae, each occurring between two quires: they could therefore originate from a loss of quires. The commentary on the canticles is incomplete at the end, as the scribe states in an annotation.
The texts were written by Bernardinos Sandros from Cremona, a scribe working in Italy in the first half of the 16th century.

The manuscript belonged to the sixteenth-century archbishop of Canterbury Matthew Parker, who ascribed it, along with other Cambridge manuscripts he owned, to his predecessor as archbishop Theodore of Tarsus (d. 690) Theodore, of Tarsus, Saint, Archbishop of Canterbury, 602-690 . An annotation on the left pastedown says that the codex was brought to England from Rome by Theodore of Tarsus in 668. This assumption is clearly incorrect, given the age of the manuscript, and was rejected on these ground first by the English palaeographer and librarian Humphry Wanley (1672-1726) Wanley, Humphrey, 1672-1726 (see Easterling 1977, pp. 183-186; Easterling 2000, pp. 110-111).

msItem.title: Commentary on the Psalms
Commentarius in Psalterium
msItem.incipit: f. 1r Ἀνεπίγραφος μὲν οὖν παρ' Ἑβραίοις ὁ πρῶτος ψαλμός
msItem.explicit: f. 302v l. 3 δόξα, τιμὴ, καὶ προσκύνησις εἰς τοὺς αἰῶνας τῶν αἰώνων ἀμήν.
msItem.note: The text starts incomplete from PG 128, 73 A l. 13
the Psalms are numbered in red ink in the margins from β΄ (2) to ρν΄ (150)

there are three lacunae:
on ff. 120v l. 32-121r l. 1 προσμαρτυρεῖ τὴν δικαιοσύνην εἴτις αὐτοῖς ἐνῆν (Psalms 44-48, PG 128, 493 D 9-525 C 10)
on ff. 248v l. 32-249r l. 1 πανταχοῦ γὰρ διεδόθησαν ματικὴν παρ' αὐτῶν λαμβάνοντες (Psalms 104-106, PG 128, 1033 D 2-1068 Β 14)
on ff. 288v l. 32-289r l. 1 ἐκείνων μὲν τὰ πρωτότυπα τῷ ἀμαρτάνειν καὶ οἱ πρωτόπλαστοι (Psalms 134-140, PG 128, 1236 C 5-1272 A 5)

f. 302v ll. 8-12 Gregory of Nazianzus, Funebris oratio in laudem Basilii Magni Caesareae (orat. 43), 19.2, ll. 1-8 (F. Boulenger, Grégoire de Nazianze. Discours funèbres en l'honneur de son frère Césaire et de Basile de Césarée, Paris 1908, p. 98)

msItem.title: Commentary on the Biblical Canticles
Commentarius in Cantica
msItem.note: The title of the work is written by a later hand in the upper margin
msItem.finalRubric: f. 319r Τὰ ἐπόμενα πάντα λείπει, ὡς καὶ ἐν ἀρχῇ πολλά. Τῷ θεῷ χάρις.
msItem.note: As specified in a note by the scribe at the end of the text, it is incomplete. On ff. 320v-321r the scribe left blank spaces writing λείπει ("it is missing"), evidently due to an incomplete exemplar
The attribution of the work to Euthymius Zigabenus is uncertain

support.material:
ff. [i]-[ii] Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark:
Pitcher with one handle, and letters P D | B , surmounted by a crown and a four-leaf clover ( 65 25 ) in the centre of the folio, comparable (with different letters) to Heawood, Pot 3550 dated to 1597.
ff. 1-145, 152-152 Western paper, folded in quarto. Unidentified watermark, ( ca. 55 12 ) in the gutter.

ff. 146-151, 153-321 Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark:
Pitcher with one handle, and name SIMONET, surmounted by a four-leaf clover. ( 53 18 ) in the centre of the folio, comparable, with differencies in the letters' disposition, to Briquet, Pot 12825 which is dated to 1544/1577, or Piccard online, Pot DE7635-PO-31441, 31585, 31733
which are dated to 1542 and 1538.

ff. [iii]-[iv] Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark:
Pitcher with one handle, and letters BB, surmounted by a four-leaf clover. ( 70 25 ) in the centre of the folio, without exact parallels in the main repertoires.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern pencil foliation, in Arabic numerals, in the top right hand corner, recto: [i]-[ii] + 1-321 + [iii]-[iv].

The manuscript has also a pagination in red (crayon?), from 1 (f. 1r) to 641 (f. 321r), in the upper margin, external corner, perhaps attributable to Matthew Parker, who owned the manuscript (among the most familiar features of his manuscripts is the use of a red pencil for foliation, see Oates 1986, p. 107). The page numbers have been written only on the recto of the leaves.

collation.p: The codex consists of a bifolium, 40 quaternions, and two bifolia, the first having lost the second leaf, leaving a paper strip.
collation.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords under the text, near the gutter, by the scribe, on the verso of the folios; they are not present regularly on all the leaves.
collation.signatures: Later signatures in modern pencil, in Arabic numerals, in the lower margin, right hand corner, from 2 (f. 9r) to 40 (f. 313r).

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in fair condition. The leaves however are yellowed, and show some damage: extensive humidity and water stains are visible on ff. 1r-23v; there are moreover brown stains, see e.g. f. 168v; the ink has sometimes smeared, see e.g. f. 171r; there are also some tears, see e.g. f. 288r

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 1r-321r A single column of 32 lines. 215 130

handNote.p: ff. 1r-321 Hand A: the text has been written by Bernardinos Sandros Sandros, Bernardinos, first half of 16th century (Βερναρδῖνος Σανδρός, 16th c., first half, RGK I, 39. See also RGK II, 59; RGK III, 75) in an informal minuscule, vertical, regular in size.
The text of the Psalms is written in two different red inks, the commentary in black.

decoDesc.decoNote: Initials in ekthesis in red ink decorated with a vegetal motif, see e.g. ff. 1r, 19v-20r.
Thick minor initials, written in red ink, see e.g. f. 1v.
Small friezes in red ink are traced passim in order to fill the lines, see ff. 33v and 187r.

additions.p: A later hand indicated lacunae in the text by writing annotations in the lower margin of ff. 120v, 248v and 288v. The indications of psalms and verses are wrong.

On the left pastedown there is an annotation in Latin stating that the manuscript belonged to Theodore of Tarsus: Hoc commentarium in psalterium grecum quondam fuit codex Theodori Archiepiscopi Cantuariensis inter eos libros quos secum detulit e Roma. Circa annum domini 668 anno quinto Egberti Regis, qui Theodorus fuit sextus ab Augustino (see Summary).

On the left pastedown are also written the classmark of the codex, Ff-1-26, an annotation indicating the content, Euthymius in Psalmos gr., and, on the upper left corner, the previous classmark #.D.ε.3 as found in the Donors' book of the Cambridge University Library, MS CUL Oo.07.52. Beneath there is moreover the number 246, attributed to the codex in T. James, Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis, Londini 1600, p. 68. The number is written also on f. [i] recto.

On f. [i] recto there is a note by Abraham Whelock (Oates 1986, p. 245), dated July 1640, stating that the author of the text is Euthymius Zigabenus and citing James Ussher (1581-1656) as an authority for the identification: Liber hic Ms. si conferatur cum Euthymio impresso ipsius esse Euthymii videbitur, teste Reverendissimo Armachano die Iulii 1640.

On f. 1r, in blank spaces within the Greek text, there is an annotation indicating the previous owner of the manuscript, Matthew Parker, Archbishop of Canterbury, and the date of his gift to the Library, 1574 (see History). In the lower margin, by the same hand, there is an indication of the number of pages, partially deleted: Continet paginas 6 .

binding.p: Western modern binding, paper over couched-laminate boards, leather corners. Rebacked, spine covered with cloth, tooled in gold with shelfmark and author Euthymius.

On the upper part of the fore-edge is written
4 Psalterium graecum cum commentario

origin.p:
The manuscript was written by the scribe Bernardinos Sandros from Cremona, probably in Italy in the
first half of the 16th century.

history.provenance: It belonged to Matthew Parker Parker, Matthew, 1504-1575 , (1504-1575, Archbishop of Canterbury from 1559).
history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1574 by Matthew Parker, as stated in an annotation on f. 1r: Matthaeus Cantuariensis 1574. On the left pastedown is glued the University of Cambridge bookplate.

recordHist.source: Description (2019) draws partly on A catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge, vol. 2, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1857, p. 318.

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
